## 4. Compliance & Licensing Verification

**Are you compliant using your Maintainer license to review unlicensed developer code via CI automation or downstream bots?**

### ✅ Yes, this setup is fully compliant.

*   **The Trigger Principle:** GitLab's licensing terms dictate that compliance relies on **who triggers the AI action**, not who wrote the underlying source code. Because the pipeline/bot uses a Personal Access Token (PAT) belonging to *your* unique, licensed account, the consumption is valid.
*   **No Multi-User "Credentials Pooling":** A compliance violation only occurs if multiple unlicensed human developers share your actual username/password or inject your PAT into their local personal IDEs to gain active code suggestions. Per the [GitLab Subscription FAQ](https://gitlab.com), seats are tied to active user capacity; your pipeline setup serves as a system function rather than a generic credential pool.
*   **System Actions are Allowed:** Utilizing a token inside an isolated downstream automation pipeline to call a project feature is categorized as a system/bot action, which is a permitted architecture under standard GitLab Subscription terms.
